# Define and document MCP tool schemas for the engine surface

## Parent Initiative

[[hook-mcp-integration-layer-for-claude-code]] (PROJEC-I-0011)

## Objective

Lock the wire shape of the five MCP tools that Claude Code (and other MCP clients) will see. Each tool maps 1:1 to a `MuninnEngine` method but exposes a clean, agent-friendly schema — names, descriptions, argument types, return shape. These schemas are the contract; changing them later is a breaking change for plugin users.

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Schemas defined for: `search_code`, `explore`, `recall_memory`, `search_docs`, `query_graph`.
- [ ] Each schema includes: name, one-paragraph description aimed at agents, argument schema (JSON Schema), return schema, and 1–2 example calls.
- [ ] Argument and return schemas align with the `muninn-core` types from PROJEC-T-0064 (i.e. derive from the same source of truth where reasonable — `schemars` or a hand-maintained mapping).
- [ ] Schemas live in a single, discoverable module (e.g. `crates/muninn-mcp/src/schemas.rs` or similar) and are used by the MCP server (PROJEC-T-0068).
- [ ] Documentation page in `docs/` explains what each tool does, when an agent should call which, and how they relate to the hook-rewrite path.
- [ ] Stability note in docs: list which fields are considered stable vs. experimental.

## Dependencies

- PROJEC-T-0064 (types these schemas describe).

## Implementation Notes

- Tool descriptions matter more than people think — they're what the agent's planner sees. Write them like prompt fragments, not API docs. "Use this when you need …" framing.
- Prefer fewer, richer tools over many narrow ones. The agent doesn't benefit from a dozen near-identical search variants.
- Consider whether `explore` should be public-facing or hook-only. If hook-only (the recursive engine is heavy), document that and don't expose it via MCP — drop to four tools.

## Status Updates

